 for bestpractices and # Loading / Success / Toast Components (Status Pages)

## Overview
Create a lightweight, reusable set of status UI components for asynchronous operations across the app. Include a loading state (spinner and skeletons), a success confirmation modal, and toast notifications for errors, saves, and background job completions. These components should be visually consistent with StudySpark’s design system, accessible, responsive, and easily pluggable into any page or workflow that performs asynchronous actions (data fetches, file uploads, AI generation steps, exports, payments, etc.).

## Page Description (Full Detail)
This page concentrates on the shared status UIs used throughout the app to communicate asynchronous operation states. Goals are to provide immediate, non-intrusive feedback during loading, clear confirmation when an action succeeds, and timely, non-blocking toasts for transient messages. The UI should be:
- Lightweight and non-blocking: avoid blocking user interaction unless necessary (e.g., a critical success confirm with CTA).
- Accessible: proper ARIA roles, labels, focus management, and keyboard navigation.
- Consistently styled: align with the project’s visual language — pastel peach, muted lavender, tangerine accents, rounded shapes, and soft shadows.
- Highly reusable: props-driven customization for content, actions, durations, and variants.
- Easily testable: deterministic rendering with clear states for loading, success, and toast visibility.

UI elements and behavior:
- Loading State
  - Spinner indicator with accessible label (aria-live polite or assertive as appropriate).
  - Optional skeleton loaders for content placeholders.
  - Subtle messaging like “Loading…” with optional descriptive text.
  - Optional timeout or cancel action via a close/abort control if operation supports cancellation.
- Success Modal
  - Centered modal/dialog with a friendly success icon, title, descriptive text, and primary/secondary actions.
  - CTA to view results, download, or navigate to relevant page (configurable via props).
  - Escape/overlay click handling to close when appropriate; focus trap when open.
- Toast Notifications
  - In-app toasts that appear on top or bottom of the screen, non-modal.
  - Support for variants: success, error, info, and warning.
  - Auto-dismiss after a configurable duration with pause on hover/focus.
  - Optional action button within the toast (e.g., “Retry”, “View”) and a close button.
  - Ensure toasts do not stack into overflow; limit visible count or provide scrollable stack.
- Interaction details
  - Animations: subtle, fast transitions for entry/exit; hover states on actionable elements.
  - Keyboard accessibility: all interactive elements reachable via keyboard; focus outlines visible.
  - Visual consistency: use pill-shaped badges, rounded cards, and gradient accents per the design guidelines.

## Components to Build
- LoadingPanel
  - Props: isLoading (boolean), message (string), description (string), actionLabel (string), onCancel (optional function)
  - Behavior: renders a visually accessible loading spinner and optional skeletons; shows message/description; optional cancel button.
  - Safety: guard all arrays or lists with (items ?? []) when rendering any mapped skeletons.
- SuccessModal
  - Props: open (boolean), title (string), description (string), primaryAction ({ label, onClick }), secondaryAction (optional { label, onClick }), onClose (function)
  - Behavior: modal with a success icon, text, and two actions; trap focus while open; restore focus on close.
  - Safety: ensure any array-based content is guarded; default props to prevent null/undefined usage.
- ToastContainer
  - Props: toasts (array of { id, type, title, description, duration, action? }), onDismiss (id)
  - Behavior: renders a stack of ToastItem components; auto-dismiss after duration; pause on hover/focus; accessible announcement region.
  - Safety: initialize toasts as [] using useState<Toast[]>([]) and validate response shapes.
- ToastItem
  - Props: id, type (success|error|info|warning), title, description, duration, action? (optional { label, onClick }), onDismiss
  - Behavior: visually styled per type with correct color tokens; accessible live region; support for action button.
  - Safety: ensure description defaults to "" if undefined; guard action existence before rendering.
- StatusPageWrapper (optional helper)
  - Props: children, status (loading|success|idle), message, ... passthrough
  - Purpose: provide a unified container that can render loading/success states in a page context with consistent chrome.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks/Libraries: React (with TypeScript), state management via React hooks; no reliance on global state beyond prop drilling or context if desired.
- State management:
  - LoadingPanel uses internal isLoading prop; no internal diverging state unless necessary.
  - ToastContainer maintains a local array of toasts (or receives via props). Use useState<Toast[]>([]) with proper initialization.
  - SuccessModal controlled via open prop; ensure focus management on open/close.
- Accessibility:
  - LoadingPanel spinner has aria-label and role="status" where appropriate.
  - SuccessModal uses role="dialog" with aria-modal="true" and proper aria-labelledby/aria-describedby.
  - Toasts use aria-live="polite" region for announcements.
- Styling:
  - Use CSS-in-JS (e.g., styled-components) or CSS Modules as per project; ensure classNames are stable.
  - Colors and typography must adhere to the provided palette; ensure contrast ratios meet accessibility standards (WCAG 2.1 AA).
- Defensive coding:
  - All array operations guarded: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - API responses or props that may be undefined are validated with default values: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Initialize all array/state hooks with correct defaults: useState<Toast[]>([]) and useState<SomeType[]>([]).
  - Optional chaining for nested API data access: obj?.property?.nested.
- API integration: None required for this task. All components should be self-contained and reusable without external API calls.

### Backend
- Not required for this prompt. If needed later, define endpoints to trigger status events and push toast data via websockets or polling.

### Integration
- Export components from a single StatusUI library/module.
- Provide a default export and named exports for each component.
- Ensure props types are explicit (TypeScript interfaces) and document required vs optional fields.
- Provide example usage snippets for common flows:
  - Show loading while saving study materials.
  - Open success modal after export completes with CTA to download.
  - Dispatch a success toast after a retry succeeds; show error toast on failure.

## User Experience Flow
1. User initiates an asynchronous action (e.g., AI-generated study set, file upload, export).
2. LoadingPanel appears or the action triggers a loading state depiction (spinner plus skeletons where applicable).
3. Upon successful completion, the UI either:
   - Displays a SuccessModal with a clear CTA (e.g., “View Downloads” or “Go to Studies”).
   - Or triggers a ToastItem notification for the successful event if a full modal isn’t required.
4. If the action fails, a ToastItem with an error variant shows, possibly offering a Retry action.
5. Toasts auto-dismiss after a configurable duration but can be manually dismissed; hovering or focusing pauses dismissal as needed.
6. All components should gracefully handle rapid open/close sequences and remain accessible.

